  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Yellow Mountain River
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At dawn I break my fast at an inn, then cross the river.
    The waters stretch endless, the sky hangs dark and vast.
    Black winds rise from all directions, churning white waves—
    our boat contends with Yellow Mountain, dipping and climbing.

    The ferry folk walk steady ground like me,
    while a lone fisherman's song drifts short and long.
    Nine times nearly drowned, the tenth time crawling to shore,
    I find the village path half-hidden in the shade of elms and willows.
  footnotes:
    - The 'nine deaths and ten lives' is a classical Chinese idiom expressing miraculous survival through extreme peril.
    - Yellow Mountain likely refers to a specific geographical landmark on the river crossing, which poses particular danger to boats.
